Lessons that can still be learned from the Cuban Missile Crisis
"Thirteen Days" („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is set to open in cinemas in numerous countries soon.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it provides insights into current events – particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors at the White House together.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a site for deploying nuclear weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made during these thirteen days, as well as the decisions that could not be reached, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days in the White House.
Recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the premiere of the film in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion session that was supposed to discuss the film as well as the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this session included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a Harvard history professor who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard professor of Political Science who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Additionally, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the film's treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the discussion participants agreed that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures President Kennedy faced, as they actually were.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in case of a crisis, but it is solely the president who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be shown, which were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an adversary thinks; in addition, the communication lines must remain open.
To corner an adversary without keeping diplomatic channels open, which allow you to understand the adversary's situation, could turn out to be disastrous.
· The United States is dependent on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, other allies, and the world's opinion supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were carefully examined and weighed was crucial to the outcome.
But would such a period of time for consideration still exist today in light of the mass media that currently exist?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the adversary's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade, which Kennedy had imposed on Cuba, was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intent, and not as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station rockets on Cuba merely reflected this policy.
But Kennedy showed fear regarding the consequences that a Soviet missile deployment on Cuba would have regarding Berlin.
The pressure of atomic weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"The Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban crisis," claimed the historian Ernest May.
"It will soon be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the missiles – as they assumed – were still en route to Cuba by sea.
An approximately 180,000-man strong U.S. troop was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombardment, which would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. „I needed thirty years,” said McNamara, „to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 were strategic nuclear warheads.”
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about this?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro answered: „I knew about it.
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba.”
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba be reduced to ashes, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion would therefore have potentially resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government did not have sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often happens when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the USA.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was limited: aircraft of the U-2 type, flying over Cuban airspace, were shot down despite explicit instructions from the Chairman to the contrary.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis exhibited a more rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
Today's discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible, yet entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the Internet, where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
